    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and trace.csv. For metric.csv: for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 using the full available series. Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2020-04-11 00:00:00+08:00 through 2020-04-11 00:30:00+08:00 (inclusive). For each group, detect anomaly points where value >= group_P95. Aggregate anomalies per group and return at most top 20 groups with anomaly_count>0, sorted by anomaly_count desc, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, group_P95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, first_anomaly_value, max_anomaly_value. For trace.csv: compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using full series. Then filter to the same incident window. Define trace anomaly if (trace_name contains 'error' or 'err') and value>0 OR value >= group_P95. Aggregate and return at most top 20 trace groups with anomaly_count>0, sorted by anomaly_count desc, with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, group_P95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, first_anomaly_value, max_anomaly_value. Keep outputs compact (one row per group)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The last Executor run computed global P95 per component-KPI and flagged anomaly points in the incident window (2020-04-11 00:00:00+08 to 00:30:00+08). The outputs show many groups with anomaly_count equal to full window sample counts; however many of those are flagged only because group_P95 == 0 (so zero-valued series were considered anomalous). Trace error_rate groups are also dominated by group_P95 == 0 and thus not informative. Separately, some metric groups have non-trivial P95 and non-zero values: notably db_007 has Hang=1 and On_Off_State=1 with group_P95=1 and anomaly_count=30 (earliest 2020-04-11 00:00:00+08). These binary flags (Hang/On_Off_State) are strong candidates for a real fault. According to the diagnosis workflow, we must now perform fault identification: locate consecutive anomalous sub-series (fault segments) for candidate components and confirm the earliest occurrence time and severity. To keep outputs compact and focused, we should first inspect all KPIs for db_007 within the incident window and compute consecutive-anomaly statistics (longest consecutive run, start time of that run, earliest anomaly time, and max value during that run) using the precomputed group_P95 thresholds already derived.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously computed global group P95s, analyze only db_007. For each KPI of db_007 available in metric.csv: 1) compute the group's global P95 using the full series (do not recalculate from filtered window), 2) filter db_007 rows to the incident window 2020-04-11 00:00:00+08 through 2020-04-11 00:30:00+08 inclusive, 3) mark each row as anomalous if value >= group_P95 (for KPIs with group_P95==0 treat anomalous as value>0 to avoid flagging zeros; for obvious binary flags you may treat value==1 as anomalous), 4) compute per-KPI aggregates: group_P95, total_anomaly_count (in window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, longest_consecutive_anomaly_length, start_timestamp_of_longest_consecutive_anomaly, max_value_within_longest_consecutive_anomaly. Return one row per KPI for db_007, sorted by longest_consecutive_anomaly_length desc. Limit output to top 20 rows. Keep output compact with only the columns specified above."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step inspected db_007 KPIs within the incident window and found strong, sustained anomalies: Hang==1 and On_Off_State==1 for the entire 00:00–00:30 window (30 min), MEM_Total continuously high across the window, and notable sustained runs for Proc_User_Used_Pct (~00:05–00:16) and Sess_Connect (~00:07 onward). These indicate the DB instance db_007 experienced a continuous problem starting at the beginning of the incident window (earliest anomaly timestamp = 2020-04-11 00:00:00+08). To confirm whether this DB problem propagated to clients and to pinpoint the exact occurrence time and likely reason (e.g., DB hung/closed vs. connection limits), we need trace evidence showing JDBC latency or errors in caller containers/services. Specifically, check trace groups that contain 'jdbc' to see whether JDBC durations or error indicators across docker_* show anomalies temporally aligned with db_007's anomalies. This will help confirm db_007 as the root cause and whether the failure is a DB hang/close (service-level failure) rather than network or CPU.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Select trace groups where trace_name contains 'jdbc'. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group compute the group's global P95 using the full series. Then filter trace rows to the incident window 2020-04-11 00:00:00+08 through 2020-04-11 00:30:00+08 inclusive. Mark a trace row as anomalous if value >= group_P95 OR (trace_name contains 'error' and value>0). Aggregate per group and return at most top 20 rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, group_P95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, first_anomaly_value, max_anomaly_value. Keep output compact (one row per group)."
}

I reviewed the metric and trace analysis: db_007 shows Hang==1 and On_Off_State==1 continuously starting at 2020-04-11 00:00:00+08, MEM_Total anomalous throughout the window, and application-side JDBC latency spikes on multiple docker containers follow these DB-side signals. This strongly indicates the DB process became unresponsive/closed at the start of the incident window.

